1.14 seniority

  • Rows represent different income brackets (e.g., “50万円未満”, “50～100万円未満”, etc.).
  • Columns 2015–2023 indicate the percentage of workers in each income bracket by year.
  • The first column “年齢（7区分）” is currently “総計” (total) for all rows, and the columns “役職” and “雇用契約期間” are NaN, suggesting that this is national-level summary data for income distribution, not broken down by position or contract length in this table.
  • The column “Attribute” identifies the income class per row (e.g., “100～200万円未満” = ¥1M–2M annual salary).

The dataset in seniority.xlsx provides annual income distribution percentages across different wage brackets from 2015 to 2023. Although it is presented at the aggregate level (年齢: 総計), the distributional structure of wages revealed in this file is essential for defining the seniority waging burden—a central concept in this research.

In the context of Japan’s seniority-based wage system, higher wage brackets are typically associated with older workers who have advanced in tenure and rank, in line with lifetime employment traditions. Over time, as the workforce ages and the proportion of older employees increases, the concentration of workers in higher salary brackets will also rise—placing financial pressure on firms and distorting wage balance across generations.

This dataset will therefore be used to construct a “seniority waging burden dummy”—a binary variable indicating whether a particular group-year combination exceeds a certain threshold of wage concentration in senior brackets.

file_list <- list.files(path = folder_path, pattern = "\\.xlsx$", full.names = TRUE)

read_long_format <- function(file_path) {
  variable_name <- tools::file_path_sans_ext(basename(file_path))
  cat("Reading:", variable_name, "\n")

  df <- tryCatch(read_excel(file_path, sheet = 1), error = function(e) return(NULL))
  if (is.null(df) || nrow(df) == 0) {
    cat("  ❌ Failed to read or empty:", variable_name, "\n")
    return(NULL)
  }

  df <- df %>%
    rename(Age_Group = 1, Category = 2) %>%
    pivot_longer(cols = matches("^20"), names_to = "Year", values_to = "Raw_Value") %>%
    mutate(
      Variable = variable_name,
      Value_type = if_else(str_detect(Raw_Value, "%"), "percent", "count"),
      Value = str_remove_all(Raw_Value, "[％%]"),
      Value = str_replace_all(Value, ",", "."),
      Value = str_trim(Value),
      Value = iconv(Value, from = "", to = "UTF-8", sub = NA_character_),
      Value = suppressWarnings(as.numeric(Value)),
      Value = if_else(Value_type == "percent", Value / 100, Value),
      Year = as.numeric(Year)
    )

  if (nrow(df) == 0) {
    cat("  ⚠️ No usable data in:", variable_name, "\n")
    return(NULL)
  }

  cat("  ✅ Loaded:", nrow(df), "rows\n")
  return(df)
}
all_data_long <- map_dfr(file_list, read_long_format)

Interpretation:

The descriptive statistics table provides a high-level summary of each key labor-related variable observed in the Japanese Panel Survey of Employment Dynamics (JPSED) from 2015 to 2023. It reports the mean, standard deviation, minimum, and maximum of each variable’s observed value, which is mostly expressed as proportions (e.g., 0.083 represents 8.3%). This helps us understand the overall distribution and variability of each measure across different years and age groups.

For instance, the variable annualsalary, which captures the distribution of income categories, has a mean value of 0.083 and a standard deviation of 0.099. This indicates that, on average, each income bracket receives about 8.3% of the population share, but there is moderate variability across groups, likely due to differences in age, contract type, and employment history. The minimum value observed is 0, while the maximum is 0.509, suggesting that in some years or age groups, more than half of the workers fall into a particular income category — possibly highlighting wage concentration among specific demographics such as older workers or full-time employees.

The jobchange variable shows a mean of 0.099, with a standard deviation of 0.136 and a maximum value as high as 0.852. This wide spread and high upper bound indicate significant heterogeneity in job change behavior. The data suggest that while job mobility is relatively low on average (9.9%), some age groups or time periods experience very high turnover — potentially among younger or precariously employed workers.

In contrast, employeesize, which refers to the size of the company in which the individual is employed, has a mean of 0.124 and a relatively low standard deviation of 0.073, with a maximum of 0.412. This suggests that while company size does influence the distribution, it is a more stable factor across demographic groups compared to variables like job change or contract type.

The position variable, with a mean of 0.062 and a standard deviation of 0.088, shows that managerial or high-ranking roles are relatively rare across the dataset but display notable variability depending on age and tenure. The maximum value of 0.507 implies that in some strata — most likely older or long-tenured employees — over half of the group may occupy higher positions, aligning with seniority-based promotion systems in Japanese firms.

Overall, this summary confirms a pattern consistent with the Japanese labor market’s dual structure. Variables associated with career advancement and security, such as salary and position, show skewed but predictable distributions with moderate variability. In contrast, variables linked to instability, such as job changes or type of employment, exhibit greater volatility and disparity, underscoring structural segmentation between stable, full-time employment and more fluid non-regular roles.

These descriptive statistics lay the foundation for deeper analyses, such as assessing the long-term sustainability of seniority-based systems or identifying which demographic groups are most affected by structural labor market changes.

This is a crucial step in understanding temporal patterns and structural changes in Japan’s labor market over the observed period, 2015–2023.

From the plots, we can see that variables such as annualsalary and position show a general increasing trend in their mean values. This may reflect the growing wage share and managerial roles among older employees, supporting the hypothesis of rising seniority burden. However, even these variables show minor variations over time, hinting at slow but steady structural shifts in the composition of Japan’s workforce.

Interpretation: The section “Mean & SD by Age Group” explores how different labor market variables vary across age cohorts, providing a deeper look into intergenerational patterns of inequality and workforce composition. This analysis is essential for evaluating whether seniority-based wage systems disproportionately favor specific age groups, particularly older cohorts, as Japan’s society continues to age.

For instance, we observe that the mean values for annualsalary and position variables increase with age until the late 50s or early 60s, after which the averages plateau or even decline. This reflects structural rigidity in late-career stages, perhaps due to limited reemployment prospects or cultural norms tied to loyalty and stability.

Ranks variables by relative variability (coefficient of variation = SD/mean).

Interpretation:

The “Coefficient of Variation (CV)” is a key metric used to assess the relative dispersion of data by comparing the standard deviation to the mean. It provides a standardized measure of variability regardless of the unit or magnitude of the variable, making it particularly useful when comparing multiple variables with different scales or meanings.

In this analysis, the CV was calculated for each of the 14 variables across the dataset. The results reveal important insights into the relative stability or volatility of each labor indicator over time and across age groups.

Notably, variables such as jobchange, employmentintention, and workinghours exhibit relatively high coefficients of variation (CV values above 0.6), suggesting significant variability in these indicators. This likely reflects individual and age-group differences in labor mobility, career uncertainty, and flexible working arrangements in Japan’s increasingly diverse employment landscape.

On the other hand, variables like gender, education, and position have low CVs, indicating relatively stable distributions across age groups and over time. This may be attributed to structural characteristics of Japanese labor markets, where gender and educational distributions shift slowly, and positions (likely measured as a percentage of managerial or non-managerial roles) remain fairly consistent due to organizational hierarchy.

Importantly, annualsalary and employeesize fall in the mid-range of CVs. This suggests that while salary and firm size vary somewhat, they do not exhibit extreme dispersion. However, given Japan’s seniority-based wage tradition, salary might still trend upward with age, while variation within age groups is more muted.

3.5 Boxplot of Value Distributions by Age Group

Shows median, interquartile range, and outliers per age group for each variable.

output_dir <- "JPSED_Boxplots"
if (!dir.exists(output_dir)) dir.create(output_dir)

variables <- unique(all_data_clean$Variable)

for (var in variables) {
  df_plot <- all_data_clean %>% filter(Variable == var)

  p <- ggplot(df_plot, aes(x = Age_Group, y = Value)) +
    geom_boxplot(outlier.shape = 16, outlier.size = 1.5, fill = "skyblue") +
    labs(
      title = paste("Boxplot of", var, "by Age Group"),
      x = "Age Group",
      y = "Value"
    ) +
    theme_minimal(base_size = 11) +
    theme(
      axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1),
      plot.title = element_text(size = 13)
    )

  print(p) 

  ggsave(
    filename = paste0(output_dir, "/", var, "_boxplot.png"),
    plot = p,
    width = 6,
    height = 4,
    dpi = 300
  )
}

Interpretation:

The boxplot visualization provides a comparative look at how various labor-related indicators are distributed across different age groups. Each boxplot reflects the central tendency and dispersion of a specific variable for each age cohort, showing not just averages but the spread and outliers in the data.

From the plots, younger age groups (e.g., 20s and 30s) tend to exhibit wider variance in indicators such as employment intention, working hours, and job change rates. This suggests greater instability or diversity in employment behavior among younger workers—likely due to career exploration, education transitions, or a rise in non-regular employment forms.

In contrast, older age groups (50s and 60s+) show more concentrated distributions, especially for variables like position, annual salary, and employment contract length. This is consistent with expectations under a seniority-based system, where older workers stabilize in long-term roles with higher pay and formal employment contracts.

Some variables—like gender share and education level—maintain consistent distributions across all age groups, indicating that these structural demographic patterns change slowly, if at all, with age.

Overall, these boxplots not only reinforce the intergenerational disparities in labor conditions but also help identify which age groups exhibit greater volatility in specific variables. These insights are particularly useful for understanding the impact of demographic aging on Japan’s labor market, and the visual structure of the boxplots makes it easier to spot potential vulnerabilities or shifts in the employment system.

3.6 Heatmap of Value Distribution by Age and Year

Visualizes intensity and patterns of each variable using color gradients.

output_dir <- "JPSED_Heatmaps"
if (!dir.exists(output_dir)) dir.create(output_dir)


variables <- unique(all_data_clean$Variable)

for (var in variables) {
  df_plot <- all_data_clean %>%
    filter(Variable == var)

  p <- ggplot(df_plot, aes(x = Year, y = Age_Group, fill = Value)) +
    geom_tile(color = "white") +
    scale_fill_viridis_c(option = "C", na.value = "grey90") +
    labs(
      title = paste("Heatmap of", var),
      x = "Year",
      y = "Age Group",
      fill = "Value"
    ) +
    theme_minimal(base_size = 10) +  # smaller base font
    theme(
      axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1),
      plot.title = element_text(size = 12),
      legend.title = element_text(size = 10),
      legend.text = element_text(size = 8)
    )

  print(p)  # Show in viewer

  # Save each plot with smaller dimensions (e.g. 6x4 inches)
  ggsave(
    filename = paste0(output_dir, "/", var, "_heatmap.png"),
    plot = p,
    width = 6,
    height = 4,
    dpi = 300  # optional for sharper images
  )
}

Interpretation:

The heatmap visualization captures how each labor-related variable fluctuates over both time (2015–2023) and age cohorts, offering a dense but highly informative view of trends and demographic shifts in Japan’s labor market. Each cell’s color intensity reflects the relative magnitude of the variable’s value—darker shades signify higher values, and lighter shades indicate lower ones.

One of the most noticeable patterns is that elderly age groups (60–70+) consistently show increasing intensities over the years in variables such as employment status, position, and employment contract period. This suggests a structural shift toward retaining or employing older individuals longer in the workforce—likely due to the policy emphasis on elderly employment in Japan’s super-aged society.

Conversely, younger age groups often display declining or more stable patterns in key categories like annual income, position, and working hours, indicating stagnation or contraction in opportunities. This could imply rising intergenerational disparities, where seniority-based structures continue to reward tenure over performance or age.

The temporal axis (Year) reveals systemic change as well. For instance, the years following 2020 show sharper changes in several variables, possibly reflecting COVID-19’s impact on employment structures, with shifts toward more non-regular employment and altered job intentions.

Overall, the heatmap acts as a powerful diagnostic tool. It highlights where structural pressure is building—particularly in the increasing burden of seniority in older cohorts. This visualization effectively underpins the hypothesis that the continued expansion of elderly employment under traditional wage structures may lead to unsustainable outcomes unless systemic reforms are considered
